# ── SweetOps local stack configuration example ───────────────────────────────
#
# Copy to `.env` and adjust for your machine. `.env` is git-ignored (see
# .gitignore); only `*.env.example` files are tracked. Every value below is a
# LOCAL DEVELOPMENT PLACEHOLDER. Never commit a real secret to this repository.
#
# Scope of this file
# ------------------
# This is the repo-root file: it documents the values that describe the local
# stack as a whole (Docker Compose, and which URLs each surface talks to).
#
#   * Backend settings           → apps/api/.env.example (copy to apps/api/.env)
#   * Frontend settings          → see "Frontend applications" at the bottom;
#                                  Next.js reads them per app, NOT from here.
#
# Only variables that the repository actually reads are listed. See
# docs/PRODUCTION_READINESS.md for the full environment checklist.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Docker Compose — PostgreSQL
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# These must match docker-compose.yml. They are the local development database
# credentials and are deliberately weak; a deployed environment must use its own
# managed credentials supplied through the platform's secret store.
POSTGRES_USER=sweetops
POSTGRES_PASSWORD=sweetops_password
POSTGRES_DB=sweetops_db

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Database and cache URLs
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Read by the API (app/core/config.py) and by every script under scripts/.
#
# Use the `localhost` form when you run the API, pytest, Alembic, the seed script
# or the reconcilers ON YOUR MACHINE against the Compose database:
DATABASE_URL=postgresql://sweetops:sweetops_password@localhost:5432/sweetops_db
REDIS_URL=redis://localhost:6379/0
#
# Use the service-name form when the process runs INSIDE Compose (this is what
# docker-compose.yml already injects into the `api` container):
#   DATABASE_URL=postgresql://sweetops:sweetops_password@postgres:5432/sweetops_db
#   REDIS_URL=redis://redis:6379/0

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Frontend applications (Next.js)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Next.js loads env files PER APP, not from the repo root. To override a default,
# create the (git-ignored) file for that app — e.g. `apps/owner-web/.env.local` —
# and put the variables there. Both have working localhost defaults compiled in,
# so a standard local run needs no file at all.
#
# NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL — REST base URL of the FastAPI backend.
#   Used by: customer-web, kitchen-web, cashier-web, owner-web.
#   Default: http://localhost:8000
#
# NEXT_PUBLIC_WS_URL — kitchen WebSocket endpoint.
#   Used by: kitchen-web, owner-web.
#   Default: ws://localhost:8000/ws/kitchen
#
# If you change either of these to a non-localhost origin, you MUST also add the
# frontend's origin to STAFF_TRUSTED_ORIGINS / PUBLIC_TRUSTED_ORIGINS in
# apps/api/.env — cookie auth uses an explicit credentialed allow-list and the
# WebSocket handshake validates the browser Origin. Neither ever accepts "*".
#
# Dev ports (see package.json): customer-web 3001, kitchen-web 3002,
# owner-web 3003, cashier-web 3004, API 8000.
